I believe there is a high probability that at least one article of impeachment will pass the house in this timeline based primarily on comparisons with the Clinton impeachment trial. In the Clinton trial, changes to the scope of the impeachment investigation were made Dec 1, 1998 and a house vote on impeachment was still held by Dec 19. Therefore, as of today, 12/5/19, there is still enough time to draft articles, move them through the judiciary committee and hold a house vote before Jan 1, 2020. The democrats also have the numbers in the judiciary committee and house (233 seats and need only 216 votes) to pass these measures (Clinton impeachment votes followed party lines). Lastly, there has been a vocal push to conclude the impeachment proceedings before the end of the year, thus showing strong motivation to conclude the process in this timeline. There is less than 100% chance due to some event stretching the process passed January 1 as well as a very small chance enough Democrats will vote against it.

I think this article does a great job of articulating a key element of the "NO" argument. I see there is a rush to a higher probability as the house process moves forward, and perhaps that will prove to be correct, but I'm struggling to see a smart STRATEGIC argument for why the Democrats should pass articles by EOY. There are plenty of moral arguments, but my framework for approaching this question is that politicians are driven primarily by (in descending order of importance) 1) what's good for their personal reelection prospects; 2) what's good for holding onto the house in 2020; 3) what will help them pick up seats in the Senate in 2020; and 4) what's good for winning the Presidency in 2020.

House Intelligence has to write a report of its findings - which it can do during the November recess. HI also has to pass its info - open door and closed door testimony - to House Judiciary in some indexed & searchable fashion - which can also be worked upon during November recess. HJ will probably formally receive all this on Dec 3 - first day the House is back in session. That's one day. They will probably want a public hearing where Schiff and others will formally present HI's findings. That's two days. Maybe here HJ might roll into debate and witnesses on what is an impeachable offense and the role of both houses of Congress - which eats up another day Then HJ has to have a formal consideration of any articles themselves - I imagine this also is in open session. That's probably another two days. Extra time would be needed on the articles themselves, and possible cross-chamber collaboration. Another day? Then HJ would vote on the articles, and send any articles to the full House. This can be done in one day - but it's still one full day. Upon which the Speaker will schedule debate, limit time frame for same, and ultimately, schedule and hold a floor vote. This looks like a three day process minimum.
